Oceania
-------
[5] Australia (NS)
Date: Tue 24 Sep 2013
Source: ABC 7 News [edited]
http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/19082400/measles-warning-for-sydney-after-3-cases-in-inner-west/


New South Wales Health has issued a warning for measles after 3 young men were diagnosed with the highly contagious virus in Sydney last week. The 3 men, aged in their 20s and 30s, recently spent time around Earlwood, Hurlstone Park, Alexandria and Waterloo in the city's inner west.

They visited medical centres in Rozelle, Croydon, and the Royal Prince Alfred emergency department while they were infectious. The health department says symptoms can take up to 21 days to appear and is warning unvaccinated people to be on the lookout for signs of the disease. Director of Communicable diseases Doctor Vicky Sheppeard says there is a real risk others have been infected.

"The symptoms that arise with measles are fever, cough, runny nose and sore red eyes, and they start around 10-14 days after you're exposed," she said. "Then 3 to 4 days later, a red, blotchy rash arises and starts on the face and then spreads to the trunk and then to the limbs."

